"""
MKT Original Commentary — 1 Samuel chapters 19–21
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-1samuel-19-21-fill.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/1samuel.json
- data/translation/glossary-hebrew.json (ḥesed, rûaḥ, tərāpîm, leḥem happānîm)
- data/translation/draft/mediating/1samuel.json (MKT text)

Key decisions in this range:
- 19:9 rûaḥ rāʿāh mēʾēt YHWH: "evil spirit from YHWH" — retain the divine agency
  without softening it; the Hebrew is unambiguous; theological difficulty acknowledged
- 20:8,14-15 ḥesed: "covenant loyalty/steadfast love" — the repeated ḥesed requests
  establish the theological vocabulary that will govern the David-Mephibosheth story (2 Sam 9)
- 21:4-6 leḥem happānîm: "bread of the Presence" — Jesus cites this episode in Matt 12:3-4;
  the translation choice (Presence rather than Showbread) is noted
- 19:13 tərāpîm: "household idols" — significant that Michal possessed them; not softened
- 19:24 nakedness: the Hebrew simply says Saul stripped his garments (bəgādāyw) and lay naked
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

SAMUEL = {
  "19": {
    "1": "<p><em>wayyədabbēr šāʾûl ʾel-yônāṯān bənô wəʾel-kol-ʿăḇādāyw ləhāmîṯ ʾeṯ-Dāwîḏ</em> — the verb <em>hāmît</em> (Hiphil of <em>mûṯ</em>, to cause to die) is official and premeditated, not a heat-of-the-moment impulse. The command goes to Jonathan and all the servants simultaneously — a public execution order. The narrative irony is immediate: Jonathan, the designated heir Saul is trying to protect, will become David&rsquo;s defender.</p>",
    "2": "<p><em>wayyaggēḏ Yônāṯān ləDāwîḏ</em> — &ldquo;Jonathan told/reported to David.&rdquo; The verb <em>nāgaḏ</em> (H5046, to declare openly) is the standard word for formal disclosure. Jonathan&rsquo;s act is not disobedience to his father but an act of covenantal loyalty to David that takes precedence — a conflict of obligations that the narrator presents without condemning Jonathan.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Jonathan&rsquo;s plan: <em>waʾănî ʾēṣēʾ wəʿāmaḏtî ʾeṣel-ʾāḇî</em> — &ldquo;I will go out and stand beside my father.&rdquo; He positions himself as a visible mediator, physically between Saul and the field where David hides. The phrase <em>wəʾăḏabberāh bəḵā</em> — &ldquo;I will speak for you&rdquo; — frames Jonathan as David&rsquo;s legal advocate (<em>mēlîṣ</em>-like function) before the king.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jonathan&rsquo;s intercession opens with <em>ʾal-yeḥṭāʾ hammelek bəʿaḇdô ḇəDāwîḏ</em> — &ldquo;let not the king sin against his servant David.&rdquo; The verb <em>ḥāṭāʾ</em> (to miss the mark/sin) reframes what Saul contemplates as a theological offense, not merely a political or personal action. <em>ʿaḇdô</em> (his servant) appeals to the covenant relationship between king and loyal retainer.</p>",
    "5": "<p><em>wayyāśem ʾeṯ-napšô bəḵappô</em> — &ldquo;he put his life in his hand&rdquo; — the idiom for risking death (<em>nāpāš</em> as the seat of life, <em>kap</em> as the palm/cupped hand). Jonathan&rsquo;s advocacy rests on the factual record: David risked his life, YHWH won a great victory (<em>yəšûʿāh gədôlāh</em>), and Saul himself witnessed it. The appeal to eyewitness testimony structures the argument legally.</p>",
    "6": "<p><em>wayyišmaʿ šāʾûl bəqôl Yônāṯān</em> — &ldquo;Saul listened to Jonathan&rsquo;s voice.&rdquo; <em>šāmaʿ bəqôl</em> (hear + in the voice of someone) is the biblical idiom for obedient heeding — more than hearing, it means yielding. Saul swears an oath by YHWH: <em>ḥay-YHWH ʾim-yûmāṯ</em> — &ldquo;as YHWH lives, he shall not die.&rdquo; The oath formula invokes YHWH as guarantor; its subsequent violation by Saul deepens the portrait of a man who treats YHWH&rsquo;s name as an instrument.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Jonathan brings David back to Saul, and David resumes court service. The reconciliation is genuine but temporary — narratively it sets up the relapse of vv.9-10. The <em>wayyəhî šālôm</em> (and there was peace) of the restored situation is fragile; the Hebrew use of the perfect tense signals a completed state that will be undone.</p>",
    "8": "<p>War resumes; David&rsquo;s military success is described with <em>wayyak bāhem makkāh gədôlāh</em> (he struck them with a great blow). The formulaic victory phrase (cf. 14:31) frames David&rsquo;s battlefield role as ongoing — he remains the indispensable warrior even as Saul turns murderous.</p>",
    "9": "<p><em>rûaḥ YHWH rāʿāh ʾel-šāʾûl</em> — &ldquo;an evil spirit from YHWH came to Saul.&rdquo; The construction is the same as 16:14-16: <em>rûaḥ rāʿāh mēʾēt YHWH</em>. Hebrew theology does not assign ultimate causation to any power independent of YHWH; the &ldquo;evil&rdquo; spirit is divine in origin. Whether this means YHWH sent it directly or permitted it is a genuine theological debate — but the grammar attributes it to YHWH without hesitation. The result is Saul&rsquo;s violent episode with the spear.</p>",
    "10": "<p><em>wayyəḇaqēš šāʾûl lənakôṯ bəḥaníṯ</em> — &ldquo;Saul sought to pin David with the spear.&rdquo; The verb <em>nāḵāh</em> (Hiphil, to strike/pin) with a spear (<em>ḥănîṯ</em>) occurs three times in this narrative cluster (18:11; 19:10; 20:33); each repetition deepens the portrait of Saul&rsquo;s escalating violence. <em>wayyippaṭēr mippenê šāʾûl</em> — &ldquo;he escaped from before Saul&rdquo; — <em>pāṭar</em> (H6452) means to slip away/escape; a different verb from the usual <em>nûs/brāḥ</em>, suggesting a close, narrow escape.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Saul sends agents (<em>malʾāḵîm</em>) to watch David&rsquo;s house through the night. The intelligence apparatus of Saul&rsquo;s court is now deployed against YHWH&rsquo;s anointed. <em>ləšomrô wəhămîṯô babbōqer</em> — &ldquo;to watch him and kill him in the morning.&rdquo; Michal&rsquo;s warning is the domestic counterpart to Jonathan&rsquo;s public advocacy — the entire household conspires to protect David.</p>",
    "12": "<p><em>wattōreḏ ʾeṯ-Dāwîḏ bəʿaḏ haḥallôn</em> — &ldquo;she let David down through the window.&rdquo; The window-escape is a recurring biblical motif for protected flight: Rahab&rsquo;s spies (Josh 2:15), Paul in Damascus (2 Cor 11:33). <em>wayyēleḵ wayyānos wayyimmālēṭ</em> — three rapid verbs (he went, he fled, he escaped) marking the urgency and success of the escape.</p>",
    "13": "<p><em>tərāpîm</em> (H8655, household idols/teraphim) — Michal places the idol in David&rsquo;s bed with a cushion of goat hair at its head to mimic a sleeping figure. The <em>tərāpîm</em> were household divine images, associated with family religion and divination (cf. Gen 31:19-35; Ezek 21:21). Their presence in David&rsquo;s house is notable and unremarked; the narrative assumes their existence without condemnation here, though later reforms will prohibit them (1 Sam 15:23; 2 Kgs 23:24).</p>",
    "14": "<p>Michal&rsquo;s lie: <em>ḥôleh hûʾ</em> — &ldquo;he is sick.&rdquo; The deception is a protective lie. The verb <em>ḥālāh</em> (H2470, to be sick/weak) uses the same root as the adjective; the simple statement buys time. The messengers accept it and report back without entering.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Saul escalates: bring him to me in his bed — <em>bammittāh</em> — so I can kill him. The persistence of the murderous intent even after Jonathan&rsquo;s successful intercession (v6) confirms that Saul&rsquo;s oath was temporary capitulation, not genuine repentance.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The deception is discovered: messengers enter and find the <em>tərāpîm</em> and goat hair. The elaborate domestic deception — household idol as body double — has a darkly comic quality; it also demonstrates Michal&rsquo;s resourcefulness and her readiness to lie to her father to protect her husband.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s confrontation with Michal: <em>lāmmāh kākāh rimmîṯinî</em> — &ldquo;why have you deceived me thus?&rdquo; <em>rāmāh</em> (H7411, to deceive/betray) is a strong word — the same root used of Laban&rsquo;s deception of Jacob (Gen 29:25). Michal&rsquo;s excuse — &ldquo;he said he would kill me if I didn&rsquo;t let him go&rdquo; — is likely a further lie; the narrator records it without endorsing it.</p>",
    "18": "<p>David&rsquo;s flight to Samuel at Ramah: <em>wayyaggēḏ lô ʾēṯ kol-ʾăšer ʿāśāh lô šāʾûl</em> — &ldquo;he told him everything Saul had done to him.&rdquo; The <em>nāgaḏ</em> (declare) vocabulary marks David&rsquo;s report as an official complaint to his spiritual authority. Naioth (nayyôṯ, perhaps &ldquo;dwellings/pastures&rdquo;) in Ramah was the site of Samuel&rsquo;s prophetic school — David seeks refuge in the prophetic community.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Saul receives intelligence about David&rsquo;s location. The <em>wayyuggaḏ ləšāʾûl</em> (it was reported to Saul) uses the same <em>nāgaḏ</em> root — information networks work in both directions. The surveillance state Saul has built turns all social relationships into potential intelligence sources.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s first group of agents: <em>wayyarəʾ ʾeṯ-lahăqaṯ hannəḇîʾîm nəḇiʾîm</em> — &ldquo;they saw the company of prophets prophesying.&rdquo; <em>lahăqāh</em> (H3862, a company/troop) is a technical term for a prophetic guild or school. <em>rûaḥ ʾĕlōhîm</em> came upon the agents, and they too began to prophesy. The irresistible divine Spirit overrides the human mission — YHWH&rsquo;s protection of David operates by co-opting his pursuers.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Second and third groups of agents are sent; both are similarly overtaken. The repetition (three groups) emphasizes the completeness of the protection and intensifies the irony: Saul&rsquo;s military resources are turned into a prophetic choir. The escalation also mirrors the plagues of Egypt — repeated divine resistance to a persistent human will.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Saul himself goes. <em>wayyišʾal wayyōmer</em> — he asks where Samuel and David are; he is told at Naioth in Ramah. The <em>bôr haggādôl</em> (great cistern) at Sechu marks the journey&rsquo;s midpoint — Saul is still determined but spatially isolated before the Spirit meets him.</p>",
    "23": "<p><em>wayyəhî rûaḥ ʾĕlōhîm ʿālāyw gam-hûʾ wayyēleḵ hālôḵ wayyiṯnaббēʾ</em> — &ldquo;the Spirit of God came upon him too, and he walked along prophesying.&rdquo; The phrase <em>hālôḵ wayyiṯnaббēʾ</em> — &ldquo;walking and prophesying&rdquo; — suggests a continuous ecstatic state during the entire journey, not just upon arrival. The Spirit overrides Saul&rsquo;s murderous intent before he reaches David.</p>",
    "24": "<p><em>wayyipšaṭ gam-hûʾ bəgādāyw wayyiṯnaббēʾ gam-hûʾ lipnê Šəmûʾēl</em> — &ldquo;he too stripped off his garments and prophesied before Samuel.&rdquo; The king lies naked (<em>ʿārôm</em>) all day and all night — total loss of royal dignity. <em>ʿal-kēn yōmərû hăgam šāʾûl bann<sup>ə</sup>ḇîʾîm</em> — &ldquo;therefore they say, &lsquo;Is Saul also among the prophets?&rsquo;&rdquo; The proverb (first heard in 10:11-12) is given its second occurrence; in context it becomes ironic commentary on a king whose divine anointing has been redirected to protect his prey.</p>"
  },
  "20": {
    "1": "<p>David&rsquo;s threefold interrogative — <em>meh-ʿāśîṯî meh-ʿăwōnî ûmeh-ḥaṭṭāʾṯî</em> — &ldquo;What have I done? What is my iniquity? What is my sin?&rdquo; The three nouns are a legal formulation of innocence: <em>ʿāwōn</em> (iniquity, moral guilt), <em>ḥēṭʾ</em> (sin, missing the mark), and the general <em>ʿāśāh</em> (wrong done). David presents himself formally as innocent before a court that has condemned him without charge.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jonathan&rsquo;s response appeals to his own position in Saul&rsquo;s confidence: <em>lōʾ-yōmar-lî ʾāḇî dāḇār gādôl ʾô dāḇār qāṭōn</em> — &ldquo;my father does nothing great or small without telling me.&rdquo; The rhetorical point is that Jonathan should know if Saul planned murder. But the dramatic irony is immediate: Jonathan&rsquo;s trusted position is precisely why Saul hides his real intent from him (v3).</p>",
    "3": "<p><em>yāḏaʿ yāḏaʿ ʾāḇîḵā</em> — emphatic construction (absolute infinitive + finite verb): &ldquo;your father knows, he truly knows.&rdquo; David sees what Jonathan cannot: that Saul conceals his intention precisely because Jonathan&rsquo;s loyalty to David is known. The phrase <em>wəḵî-penê-yənāṯān yiḵʾāḇ</em> — &ldquo;lest Jonathan be grieved&rdquo; — attributes motive to Saul: his concealment is not consideration but calculation.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jonathan&rsquo;s unconditional offer: <em>kol-ʾăšer-tōmar napšəḵā ʾeʿěśeh-llāḵ</em> — &ldquo;whatever your soul (<em>nāpāš</em>) asks, I will do for you.&rdquo; The use of <em>nāpāš</em> (soul/life) in the vow gives it covenantal depth; Jonathan commits the full weight of his life-loyalty to David&rsquo;s request.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David&rsquo;s plan: the new moon festival (<em>hāḥōdeš</em>). Attendance at the royal feast was obligatory for the inner court — absence would immediately be noticed. David uses his absence as the diagnostic: Saul&rsquo;s reaction will reveal his intentions. <em>ʾēšēḇ ʾeṣel hammeleḵ leʾĕḵôl</em> — &ldquo;I should sit with the king at the feast&rdquo; — the festival meal as a political performance of loyalty.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The alibi: a family sacrifice in Bethlehem, David&rsquo;s hometown. <em>mizbaḥ-yāmîm</em> — &ldquo;an annual sacrifice&rdquo; — a regular family sacrificial occasion (cf. Hannah&rsquo;s annual journey, 1:3). Jonathan is to present it to Saul on David&rsquo;s behalf. The alibi is plausible and theologically grounded — family sacrifice was a legitimate obligation.</p>",
    "7": "<p><em>ʾim-kōh yōmar ṭôḇ šālôm laʿaḇdəḵā</em> — &ldquo;if he says &lsquo;good,&rsquo; peace to your servant&rdquo; — the conditional structure maps two outcomes: if Saul accepts the alibi peacefully, David is safe; if he <em>yiḥar-ʾap</em> (becomes angry, lit. &ldquo;his nose burns&rdquo;), the intended evil is confirmed. <em>ḥārāh-ʾap</em> is the standard Hebrew idiom for explosive anger, with &ldquo;nose&rdquo; as the seat of breath and rage.</p>",
    "8": "<p><em>wəʿāśîṯā ḥesed ʿal-ʿaḇdəḵā</em> — &ldquo;show covenant loyalty to your servant.&rdquo; <em>ḥesed</em> (H2617) is the key theological term of this passage — the steadfast, covenantal love that binds the two together. David calls Jonathan to fulfill the specific obligations of their covenant (<em>bərît YHWH</em>, covenanted before YHWH, v8b). If David has done iniquity, Jonathan may kill him himself — the offer of self-judgment as a guarantee of good faith.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Jonathan refuses the conditional execution: <em>ḥālîlāh lāḵ</em> — &ldquo;far from it for you!&rdquo; (a strong negative expression). His promise: <em>kî ʾim-yāḏaʿ ʾēḏaʿ</em> — &ldquo;if I know for certain&rdquo; — again the absolute infinitive for certainty. Jonathan will not withhold the information; the ḥesed he has pledged includes full disclosure when needed.</p>",
    "10": "<p>David&rsquo;s practical question: <em>mî yaggîḏ lî</em> — &ldquo;who will tell me?&rdquo; The arrow signal system (vv.20-22) is developed in response to this question. The question reveals the precariousness of the situation: David cannot be at court to receive the information directly; the covenant communication must be covert.</p>",
    "11": "<p><em>lekā wənēṣēʾ haśśāḏeh</em> — &ldquo;come, let us go out to the field.&rdquo; The two leave the city for a private space. The field (<em>śāḏeh</em>) is the locus of the covenant renewal; away from court politics, the two friends speak freely. The movement from palace to open field mirrors the shift from institutional to personal covenant.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Jonathan&rsquo;s covenant oath: <em>YHWH ʾĕlōhê Yiśrāʾēl kî-ʾeḥqōr ʾeṯ-ʾāḇî</em> — &ldquo;By YHWH, the God of Israel — when I sound out my father.&rdquo; <em>ḥāqar</em> (H2713, to search out/probe) is used for careful inquiry, not confrontation. The oath invokes YHWH as guarantor: if the news is good, Jonathan will send it to David; if not, he will send that too.</p>",
    "13": "<p><em>kōh-yōsîp YHWH laYônāṯān wəḵōh yōsîp</em> — the double oath formula (may YHWH add/do more to Jonathan and more still) invokes graduated divine punishment if the oath is broken. The commitment is total: Jonathan promises to actively warn David and help him escape. <em>wahayāh YHWH ʿimmāḵ kaʾăšer hāyāh ʿim-ʾāḇî</em> — &ldquo;may YHWH be with you as he was with my father&rdquo; — Jonathan explicitly passes the divine favor from Saul to David.</p>",
    "14": "<p><em>wəʾim-ʿôdennî ḥay wəʿāśîṯā ʿimmî ḥesed YHWH</em> — &ldquo;if I am still alive, you shall show me the ḥesed of YHWH.&rdquo; Jonathan&rsquo;s request turns the ḥesed covenant around: he now asks David for the divine-quality covenant loyalty that David has been asking of him. <em>ḥesed YHWH</em> (the ḥesed of YHWH) is a higher category than human loyalty — it is the kind of love that YHWH himself shows, now required of humans toward one another.</p>",
    "15": "<p><em>wəʾal-takkrēṯ ʾeṯ-ḥasdəḵā mēʿim bêṯî ʿaḏ-ʿôlām</em> — &ldquo;do not cut off your covenant loyalty from my house forever.&rdquo; <em>kāraṯ ḥesed</em> (cut off loyalty) is the formal termination of covenant obligation. Jonathan looks beyond his own life to his descendants (<em>bêṯî</em>, my house): the covenant is intergenerational. This provision directly establishes the legal basis for David&rsquo;s care of Mephibosheth in 2 Sam 9.</p>",
    "16": "<p><em>wayyikrōṯ Yônāṯān ʿim-bêṯ Dāwîḏ</em> — &ldquo;Jonathan made a covenant with the house of David.&rdquo; The formal covenant language (<em>kāraṯ bərît</em>) frames this as a dynastic covenant, not merely a personal friendship — it extends to families and successors. <em>ûḇiqqēš YHWH miyyaḏ ʾōyəḇê Dāwîḏ</em> — &ldquo;and the LORD will require it from the hand of David&rsquo;s enemies&rdquo; — YHWH is invoked as the enforcer of the covenant&rsquo;s anti-enemy clause.</p>",
    "17": "<p><em>wayyôsep Yônāṯān lahaššbîaʿ ʾeṯ-Dāwîḏ bəʾahabāṯô ʾōṯô kî ʾahabaṯ napšô ʾăhēḇô</em> — &ldquo;Jonathan caused David to swear again because of his love, for he loved him as his own soul.&rdquo; <em>ʾahabaṯ napšô</em> — &ldquo;the love of his soul&rdquo; — echoes the standard formula for deepest personal attachment; cf. 18:1 where the same phrase first appears. The repetition (three mentions of <em>ʾāhab</em>) reinforces that this covenant rests on genuine love, not political calculation.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Jonathan outlines the logistical plan: at the new moon feast, David&rsquo;s seat will be empty (<em>nip̱qaḏtā</em>, you will be missed/your absence will be noticed). The verb <em>pāqaḏ</em> (H6485, to visit/inspect/notice absence) is often used for military musters where an absence is significant; its use here anticipates the formal occasion of the feast.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The signal location: the stone Ezel (<em>ʾeḇen hāʾāzel</em>, perhaps &ldquo;the departing stone&rdquo; or a proper name). David is to hide there on the third day. The specificity of the geographic marker — a known landmark — anchors the covert communication plan in real terrain.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Jonathan will shoot three arrows toward the stone — the number three creates plausible hunting cover. The signal is embedded in a real action that looks innocent to an observer: a young man practicing archery. The code is embedded in the spatial relationship between arrow and target: near = safe; far = flee.</p>",
    "21": "<p><em>ʾim-ʾāmōr ʾōmar lannnaʿar hinnēh haḥiṣṣîm mimmənnaḵā waqqāḥāh</em> — &ldquo;if I say to the boy, &lsquo;look, the arrows are on this side of you&rsquo;&rdquo; — the near-arrow signal means peace. <em>šālôm lāḵ wəʾên dāḇār</em> — &ldquo;peace to you and there is no thing.&rdquo; The coded message uses the simplest possible language, interpretable only by those who know the code.</p>",
    "22": "<p><em>wəʾim-kōh ʾōmar laʿelem hinnēh haḥiṣṣîm mimmənnaḵā wāhāʾlāh lēḵ kî šillaḥăḵā YHWH</em> — &ldquo;but if I say, &lsquo;the arrows are farther out,&rsquo; then go, for the LORD has sent you away.&rdquo; The far-arrow signal encodes a theological frame: David&rsquo;s departure is not a defeat but divine sending (<em>šālaḥ</em>). YHWH himself is the one dismissing David from court — his flight is obedience to divine direction.</p>",
    "23": "<p><em>wəhaddāḇār ʾăšer dibbarnû ʾănî wāʾattāh hinnēh YHWH bênenû ʿaḏ-ʿôlām</em> — &ldquo;the matter we have spoken — I and you — the LORD is between us forever.&rdquo; <em>ʿaḏ-ʿôlām</em> (to eternity) gives the covenant a trans-temporal dimension. YHWH as the standing witness (<em>YHWH bênenû</em>) means the covenant cannot be dissolved by death or changed circumstances.</p>",
    "24": "<p><em>wayyissāṯēr Dāwîḏ baśśāḏeh</em> — David hides in the field while the new moon feast proceeds at court without him. The juxtaposition of David concealed in the field and Saul at the feast underlines the divided reality: the anointed king is in hiding while the rejected king dines in state.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The seating arrangement: Saul against the wall (<em>qîr</em>), Abner beside him, Jonathan opposite, David&rsquo;s place empty. The court seating was fixed and hierarchical; David&rsquo;s empty place is a visible absence, a gap in the social body that demands explanation.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s first assumption: ritual impurity (<em>ṭāmēʾ hûʾ biltî ṭāhôr</em>). The law required ritual purity for participation in sacred meals; Saul assumes David is unclean rather than absent by choice. The initial charitable interpretation — which Saul himself knows is probably false — keeps the feast proceeding on day one.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Day two: <em>maddûaʿ lōʾ-bāʾ ben-Yišay gam-timôl gam-hayyôm ʾel-hallāḥem</em> — &ldquo;why has Jesse&rsquo;s son not come to the meal, either yesterday or today?&rdquo; The deliberate naming of David as &ldquo;son of Jesse&rdquo; (<em>ben-Yišay</em>) is a rhetorical reduction — denying David his court title, treating him as a mere commoner.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Jonathan delivers the alibi: David asked permission to go to Bethlehem for a family sacrifice. The simplicity and plausibility of the excuse is the point; Jonathan delivers it straightforwardly without elaboration, making it harder to dismiss.</p>",
    "29": "<p><em>yəšallaḥ-nā ʾōṯî</em> — &ldquo;please let me go.&rdquo; Jonathan repeats David&rsquo;s alleged words, emphasizing the family obligation: a brother insisted, a clan sacrifice required attendance. The language of <em>ʾāḥîw ṣiwwāh</em> (my brother commanded me) appeals to kin-obligation — a category Saul himself would recognize as legitimate.</p>",
    "30": "<p><em>ben-naʿăwat hammardût</em> — &ldquo;son of a perverse, rebellious woman.&rdquo; This is Saul&rsquo;s insult to Jonathan — one of the most cutting familial insults in the Hebrew Bible. <em>naʿăwāh</em> (perversity) and <em>mardût</em> (rebellion) attack the mother to shame the son. The eruption reveals what Saul has been suppressing: his certainty that Jonathan&rsquo;s loyalty to David is treason against the royal house.</p>",
    "31": "<p><em>kî kol-hayyāmîm ʾăšer ben-Yišay ḥay ʿal-hāʾădāmāh lōʾ tikkôn ʾattāh ûmalkûṯəḵā</em> — &ldquo;as long as Jesse&rsquo;s son lives, neither you nor your kingdom will stand.&rdquo; In his rage Saul involuntarily confirms YHWH&rsquo;s election of David — his own words are the best testimony to David&rsquo;s coming kingship. <em>lōʾ tikkôn</em> (will not stand/be established) uses the <em>kûn</em> root of divine establishment — the very word YHWH uses for his covenant (2 Sam 7:16).</p>",
    "32": "<p>Jonathan&rsquo;s legal defense: <em>lāmmāh yûmāṯ meh-ʿāśāh</em> — &ldquo;why should he die? What has he done?&rdquo; The twice-repeated question is the form of legal defense — demanding specification of the offense before capital punishment. Jonathan makes the procedural argument: no crime has been named.</p>",
    "33": "<p><em>wayyāṭēl šāʾûl ʾeṯ-haḥănîṯ ʿālāyw ləhakkōṯô</em> — &ldquo;Saul hurled his spear at Jonathan to strike him.&rdquo; The same violent act aimed at David (18:11; 19:10) is now aimed at his own son. The <em>ḥănîṯ</em> (spear) has become the symbol of Saul&rsquo;s disorder; its deployment against Jonathan confirms that Saul is past reason.</p>",
    "34": "<p><em>wayyaqom Yônāṯān mēʿim haššulḥān baḥărî-ʾap</em> — &ldquo;Jonathan rose from the table in fierce anger.&rdquo; <em>ḥărî-ʾap</em> (burning of nose = fierce anger) is the same idiom used of YHWH&rsquo;s wrath. Jonathan is angry and grieved (<em>kî huḵlam Dāwîḏ mēʾēt ʾāḇîw</em>) — the grief is for David&rsquo;s public shaming, not for his own near-death. The covenant loyalty continues to define Jonathan&rsquo;s emotional priority.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Jonathan goes to the field at the appointed time. <em>naʿar qāṭōn</em> (a small boy/young servant) is the instrument of the covert communication — the boy knows only the literal action, not its meaning (v39). The use of an innocent intermediary protects both parties.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Jonathan shoots the arrow that &ldquo;flew past the boy&rdquo; — the far-arrow signal. <em>wayyôreʾ haḥēṣ lahaʿăḇîrô</em> — &ldquo;he shot the arrow to make it pass beyond.&rdquo; The deliberate overshoot encodes the warning in a visible physical act that the boy carries out without understanding its significance.</p>",
    "37": "<p><em>hēn haḥēṣ mimməḵā wāhāʾlāh</em> — &ldquo;the arrow is beyond you, isn&rsquo;t it?&rdquo; The far-arrow is confirmed. The signal is deployed; the danger is real; David must go. Jonathan&rsquo;s shouted words to the boy are simultaneously a message to David — the public shout serves a double function.</p>",
    "38": "<p><em>maher ḥûšāh ʾal-tāʿmōḏ</em> — &ldquo;hurry, make haste, don&rsquo;t stop.&rdquo; The urgency escalates through three imperatives. The boy gathers the arrows and returns to the city — his errand complete, the drama continuing without his knowledge.</p>",
    "39": "<p><em>wəhannnaʿar lōʾ-yāḏaʿ məʾûmāh</em> — &ldquo;the boy knew nothing.&rdquo; This detail closes the frame of the covert communication. The narrator emphasizes the boy&rsquo;s innocence specifically to underline the technical brilliance of the signal: it was invisible as a message to everyone except its two intended recipients.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Jonathan gives his weapons to the boy and sends him away — creating the private space for the farewell. The handing off of weapons (<em>kēlāyw</em>) is significant: Jonathan has already given David his robe, armor, sword, bow, and belt in 18:4; now he removes the remaining implements of court identity.</p>",
    "41": "<p><em>wayyippōl ʾappayim ʾarṣāh wayyištaḥû šālōš pəʿāmîm</em> — &ldquo;he fell with his face to the ground and bowed three times.&rdquo; The triple prostration is a royal greeting — David addresses Jonathan with formal court honor even in the wilderness. <em>wayyiḇkû ʾîš ʾeṯ-rēʿēhû</em> — &ldquo;they wept, each with his friend.&rdquo; The mutual weeping mirrors the earlier ḥesed language: the covenant is felt as grief at separation.</p>",
    "42": "<p><em>lēḵ ləšālôm ʾăšer nišbaʿnû šənênû ʾănaḥnû bəšēm YHWH</em> — &ldquo;go in peace, for we have both sworn in the name of YHWH.&rdquo; The final word of the farewell grounds the covenant in YHWH&rsquo;s name. <em>bên yādî ûḇên yāḏəḵā ûḇên zarʿî ûḇên zarʿăḵā ʿaḏ-ʿôlām</em> — &ldquo;between me and you, between my seed and your seed, forever.&rdquo; The covenant extends to descendants; Jonathan speaks the terms of what will become the Mephibosheth arrangement.</p>"
  },
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>David arrives at Nob, the priestly city, alone. <em>wayyeḥaraḏ ʾAḥîmeleḵ liqrāʾṯ Dāwîḏ</em> — &ldquo;Ahimelech trembled to meet David.&rdquo; <em>ḥāraḏ</em> (H2729, to tremble/be frightened) signals that the priest senses something wrong in David&rsquo;s solitary arrival — no royal escort, no explanation. The question &ldquo;why are you alone, and no one with you?&rdquo; is professional, not merely curious.</p>",
    "2": "<p><em>dāḇār ṣiwwānî hammelek</em> — &ldquo;the king has commanded me on a matter.&rdquo; David&rsquo;s lie protects him at the cost of implicating Ahimelech in an act of treason (aiding an unauthorized person). <em>ûmāqôm muʿad yāḏaʿtî ʾeṯ-hannəʿārîm</em> — &ldquo;and I have told the young men the appointed place&rdquo; — David invents a detachment of soldiers waiting elsewhere; the fiction provides cover for the request that follows.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The request for bread: <em>ḥămišāh-leḥem tēn bəyāḏî ʾô hammimṣāʾ</em> — &ldquo;give me five loaves in my hand, or whatever is available.&rdquo; Five loaves is a substantial request; the &ldquo;or whatever&rdquo; signals real hunger and urgency. The number five will reappear in the NT feeding narratives (Matt 14:17).</p>",
    "4": "<p><em>ʾên-leḥem ḥōl ʾel-taḥaṯ yāḏî kî-ʾim-leḥem qōdeš</em> — &ldquo;there is no ordinary bread under my hand, but there is holy bread.&rdquo; The <em>ḥōl</em> vs. <em>qōdeš</em> distinction (profane/ordinary vs. holy/consecrated) is the central tension of the episode. The bread of the Presence (<em>leḥem happānîm</em>, Exod 25:30; Lev 24:5-9) was ritually reserved — replaced weekly, eaten by priests only. Ahimelech&rsquo;s conditional offer — if the men have kept from women — applies Numbers 5 purity logic to the emergency.</p>",
    "5": "<p><em>ʾāḵēn ḥullǎlāh libbênûš miṯmôl šilšôm</em> — &ldquo;indeed, women have been kept from us since yesterday and the day before.&rdquo; David&rsquo;s claim of ritual purity for his men is the halachic justification. Jesus will cite this episode (Matt 12:3-4; Mark 2:25-26; Luke 6:3-4) as a precedent that human need can override ceremonial law: David&rsquo;s act is cited as lawful by the Son of David — an implicit claim that he has authority to interpret Torah.</p>",
    "6": "<p><em>wayyittēn-lô hakkōhēn qōdeš</em> — &ldquo;the priest gave him holy bread.&rdquo; <em>leḥem happānîm</em> (bread of the Presence/Face) was the weekly bread set out before YHWH, renewed each Sabbath (Lev 24:8); removed bread was hot — just replaced. The hot bread given to David is the bread of the divine presence — the immediate, daily sustenance of YHWH, now given to the fugitive king. The irony: the man anointed to rule is fed by the bread of the Lord&rsquo;s own table.</p>",
    "7": "<p><em>āḏōm ʾeḏōmî</em> — Doeg the Edomite, &ldquo;detained before YHWH.&rdquo; <em>ʿāṣûr lipnê YHWH</em> (detained/kept before YHWH) may mean he is undergoing a ritual process (a vow? disease quarantine?). Whatever its cause, his presence at the sanctuary during David&rsquo;s visit is the fatal detail — he will report to Saul (22:9-10) and massacre the priests. The narrator plants this narrative bomb quietly.</p>",
    "8": "<p>David asks for a weapon: <em>ḥānîṯ ʾô-ḥereb</em> — &ldquo;a spear or sword.&rdquo; <em>kî gam-ḥarbî wəgam-kēlai lōʾ-lāqaḥtî bəyāḏî</em> — &ldquo;for I have brought neither my sword nor my equipment.&rdquo; The haste of the flight is emphasized; the king&rsquo;s champion is weaponless. The absence of David&rsquo;s own sword sets up the provision of Goliath&rsquo;s sword — a deeply ironic supply.</p>",
    "9": "<p><em>ḥereḇ Golyāṯ happəlištî ʾăšer hikkeṯā bəʿēmeq hāʾēlāh</em> — &ldquo;the sword of Goliath the Philistine whom you struck in the Valley of Elah — there it is, wrapped in a cloth behind the ephod.&rdquo; Goliath&rsquo;s sword is kept as a sacred trophy at the sanctuary. <em>ʾaḥǎrê hāʾēpôḏ</em> (behind the ephod) places it in the innermost zone of the tabernacle precinct. David receives back the sword of his greatest victory as a fugitive at his lowest point — the warrior is re-armed with his own trophy.</p>",
    "10": "<p>David flees to Achish king of Gath — the homeland of Goliath, carrying Goliath&rsquo;s sword. The audacity of the move (seeking refuge among the Philistines) is remarkable; the risk is that he will be recognized. <em>wayyāqom wayyibrāḥ bayyôm hahûʾ mippenê šāʾûl</em> — the pace of flight is immediate; &ldquo;that very day.&rdquo;</p>",
    "11": "<p>Achish&rsquo;s servants identify David: <em>hălôʾ-zeh Dāwîḏ melek hāʾāreṣ</em> — &ldquo;is this not David the king of the land?&rdquo; They quote the victory song: &ldquo;Saul has struck his thousands, and David his ten thousands.&rdquo; David&rsquo;s fame has preceded him; the Philistines know his identity and his glory — making Gath the most dangerous possible refuge.</p>",
    "12": "<p><em>wayyāśem Dāwîḏ ʾeṯ-hadəḇārîm hāʾēlleh bilibbô</em> — &ldquo;David took these words to heart.&rdquo; <em>śûm bilbāb</em> (to set in the heart) marks serious calculation. His fear of Achish is tactical — he recognized the danger and responded with the only tool available: performance.</p>",
    "13": "<p><em>wayyəšannēʾ ʾeṯ-ṭaʿmô bəʿênêhem wayyiṯhôlēl bəyādām</em> — &ldquo;he changed his behavior before them and acted as if insane.&rdquo; <em>šānāh</em> (H8138, to change) with <em>ṭaʿam</em> (reason/taste/judgment) means deliberately altering his presentation. <em>hiṯhôlēl</em> (Hitpoel of <em>hālal</em> or <em>hôlēl</em>) = to feign madness. He makes marks on the doors and lets saliva run on his beard — both behaviors associated with mental breakdown in the ancient world.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Achish&rsquo;s dismissal: <em>rəʾû ʾîš mištaggēaʿ</em> — &ldquo;look, this man is insane.&rdquo; <em>šāgaʿ</em> (H7696, to be mad) is the word used for ecstatic prophecy in negative contexts; the boundary between prophetic ecstasy and madness was culturally thin. Achish&rsquo;s reaction — &ldquo;why did you bring him to me?&rdquo; — shows that a mad person was of no political value.</p>",
    "15": "<p><em>hăḥasēr məšuggāʿîm ʾānî</em> — &ldquo;Am I short of madmen?&rdquo; Achish&rsquo;s rhetorical question dismisses David as socially worthless. The irony is deep: the man who killed Achish&rsquo;s greatest champion is dismissed as a worthless madman — survival through humiliation. The same pattern — apparent weakness concealing divine protection — runs throughout David&rsquo;s wilderness period.</p>"
  }
}

